"New landmark: The 19-foot-high sculpture Typewriter Eraser, Scale X, by Claes Oldenburg and Coosje van Bruggen rises from the Reflecting Pool at the Norton's entrance. [THOMAS CORDY/palmbeachpost.com]",
"Big art, big impression: The new Norton's expanded galleries mean large pieces can be displayed. [THOMAS CORDY/palmbeachpost.com]",
"Tote bag featuring the Norton's iconic Diana sculpture is available in the expanded museum store. [THOMAS CORDY/palmbeachpost.com]",
"There are seven architectural features to note at the new Norton Museum of Art. [THOMAS CORDY/palmbeachpost.com]",

"EAST/WEST AXIS: The new Norton returns the museum to the 1941 east/west axis conceived by original architect Marion Sims Wyeth, who built a series of Art Deco-inspired pavilions organized around a central courtyard. The original entrance faced east, toward the Intracoastal Waterway. Later additions moved the entrance to the south, disrupting the east/west axis. The new Norton entrance is on Dixie Highway. From the Great Hall near the entrance, visitors can see all the way to the Intracoastal Waterway. [Rendering by Foster + Partners]",

"REFLECTIVE CANOPY: Above the entry forecourt, called the Heyman Plaza, a 43-foot-high aluminum canopy appears to float above the entrance. The canopy extends 45 feet beyond the face of the building. It features a scallop-shaped cutout around the 65-foot-tall banyan tree. Made of aluminum panels with a special, semi-reflective coating, the canopy reflects light from the interior of the building and the Reflecting Pool below. [THOMAS CORDY/palmbeachpost.com]",

"OCULUS: The \"living room' of the museum is the Great Hall, a vast 3,600-square-foot, 43-foot-tall space with lounge seating, a coffee bar, piano, book carts — and the \"oculus,' a circular skylight with fabric that filters the light as it shines into the room. Light also comes in from the 28-foot-tall windows. Looking out, visitors can see the intricacies of the branches of the banyan tree and experience how the light changes as it filters through the leaves. [THOMAS CORDY/palmbeachpost.com]",

"SCULPTURE GARDENS: \"You're a museum and a garden\", architect Norman Foster said when he first toured the Norton. His Foster + Partners team created landscape \"niches\" for several large sculptures by famed artists such as Keith Haring. Glass walls let diners in the Leonard and Evelyn Lauder Restaurant gaze out to the lawn and the sculpture gardens.[THOMAS CORDY/palmbeachpost.com]",

"WATER, WATER, WATER: \"The Norton Museum was founded in 1941, and at the outset, it related to the ocean, says architect Norman Foster. \"Our intention has been to rediscover its essence.' The new Norton plays up the water theme with the serene Reflecting Pool surrounding the large sculpture at the entrance, Typewriter Eraser, Scale X. Inside the building, artist Rob Wynne's installation of glass bubbles climbing up the grand staircase and the Dale Chihuly ceiling featuring sea life continue the water theme. [THOMAS CORDY/palmbeachpost.com]",

"WALLS OF GLASS: The giant walls of glass are the largest hurricane-rated glass panes installed in Florida. The heaviest pieces weigh 2,300 pounds each. The glass was produced by Pilkington Europe, coated by Interpane Germany and then fabricated by Tvitec in Spain. When it was installed at the Norton, the glass had to be hurricane tested, so builders brought in a plane engine to simulate wind speeds of up to 228 mph and shot 2-by-4 boards at it. (Category 5 hurricanes start at 157 mph winds.) \"In a hurricane, the safest place to be is behind one of these glass walls,' says project manager John Backman. [THOMAS CORDY/palmbeachpost.com]",

From left to right: Ellison Onizuka, Mike Smith, Christa McAuliffe, Dick Scobee, Greg Jarvis, Ron McNair and Judy Resnick. The space shuttle Challenger exploded shortly after lifting off from Kennedy Space Center Jan. 28, 1986. All seven crew members died in the explosion, which was blamed on faulty O-rings in the shuttle's booster rockets. The disaster shattered NASA's image and the belief that flying on a spacecraft could become as routine as flying on an airplane.",
